## A Mage in Service to Skyrim

**Gauldur** was one of the most powerful archmages of the First Era in **Skyrim**, a scholar whose knowledge and magical power were revered throughout the kingdom. Living during the first decades of the First Era, when the Nordic realm was still young and fragile, Gauldur served as an advisor to the **High King** and was respected by all.

Much of his power derived from an extraordinary artifact: the **Gauldur Amulet**, a talisman he had crafted himself that greatly amplified the magical abilities of its wearer. This amulet was the source of his influence and, unfortunately, the object of the covetousness that would bring about his ruin.

Gauldur resided in an isolated tower and devoted his days to study, teaching, and political counsel. He had three sons whom he trained in the arcane arts, hoping to make them mages as accomplished as himself. This paternal trust would prove to be his greatest mistake.

## The Three Sons: Jyrik, Sigdis, and Mikrul

Gauldur's three sons — **Jyrik**, **Sigdis**, and **Mikrul** — had each developed considerable magical talents under their father's tutelage. But they also shared a fatal trait: a devouring ambition that their father's upbringing never managed to temper.

**Jyrik**, the eldest, was a master of the elemental arts and destruction magic. His raw power was terrifying, capable of unleashing storms of fire and ice with unsettling ease. He coveted the absolute power the amulet granted his father.

**Sigdis**, the middle son, excelled in the arts of illusion and conjuration. Cunning and manipulative, he created doubles of himself to deceive his enemies and used magic to bend minds to his will.

**Mikrul**, the youngest, mastered necromancy and the dark arts. He commanded the dead and drained the life force from the living — a talent that horrified even his brothers.

## The Parricide

Tragedy struck when the three brothers, united by their shared greed, conspired against their own father. Driven by the desire to seize the Gauldur Amulet, they murdered him in his own tower — an act of betrayal so monstrous it shocked all of Skyrim.

After killing Gauldur, the brothers shattered the amulet into three fragments, each taking one piece. Even fragmented, the amulet conferred considerable power on each bearer. Armed with these fragments, the three brothers went their separate ways and launched individual campaigns of terror across Skyrim.

Jyrik marched on **Saarthal** with an army, Sigdis sowed chaos in villages through his illusions and manipulations, and Mikrul raised an army of undead that ravaged the southern lands. The kingdom faced collapse under these three simultaneous scourges.

## The Hunt and the High King's Justice

Faced with this triple threat, the **High King** of Skyrim dispatched his personal champion, Archmage **Geirmund**, at the head of an elite force of warriors and mages, with orders to track down and neutralize Gauldur's three sons.

The hunt was long and bloody. Geirmund pursued the brothers one by one, confronting their powers amplified by the amulet's fragments. Each confrontation was a desperate battle.

Jyrik was tracked to **Saarthal**, where he had made his stand. The magical clash was so violent that the tunnels partially collapsed, trapping some of the pursuers. Sigdis took refuge in an ancient barrow, using his illusions to confound his enemies again and again. Mikrul barricaded himself in a crypt with his army of the dead.

One by one, the three brothers were defeated, though Geirmund himself perished in the final battle. The fragments of the amulet were removed from their bodies and sealed separately.

## The Erasure from History

What makes the story of Gauldur particularly fascinating is not only the tragedy itself, but the way it was deliberately erased from collective memory. The High King, horrified by the magnitude of the betrayal and fearing that others might seek to replicate the deeds of the patricidal sons, ordered all mention of Gauldur and his sons to be suppressed.

Documents were destroyed, bards were forbidden from singing this tale, and anyone who spoke Gauldur's name risked the death penalty. The bodies of the three brothers were sealed in separate tombs, guarded by spells and draugr, to ensure they could never be reunited.

This censorship was so effective that for millennia, the story of Gauldur survived only as incomplete fragments, rumors, and half-forgotten legends. The **Gauldur Fragment**, one of the few surviving documents, was not rediscovered until the Fourth Era.

## The Tombs and Their Guardians

The three sons were buried in separate locations, each designed to prevent any attempt to recover the amulet's fragments:

**Jyrik Gauldurson** was sealed beneath **Saarthal**, in the depths of the ruined city. His tomb is guarded by ancient draugr and magical traps tied to the earth's ley lines.

**Sigdis Gauldurson** rests in **Geirmund's Hall**, named ironically after the man who defeated him. Even in death, his powers of illusion persist, creating spectral doubles that disorient intruders.

**Mikrul Gauldurson** was entombed in **Folgunthur**, a labyrinthine burial complex infested with the undead he continues to command from beyond the grave.

## The Legacy and Rediscovery

The **Gauldur Amulet**, even fragmented, remained an object of fascination for the few scholars who knew of its existence. Reassembling it would grant its bearer immense magical power — resistance to magic, increased life force, and amplified spellcasting strength.

During the Fourth Era, the adventurer **Daynas Valen** devoted his life to finding the fragments, guided by ancient documents. His quest, though it ended in his own death, opened the way for others who would eventually succeed in reassembling the amulet.

The story of Gauldur is a warning about the dangers of unbridled ambition and blind trust. It also shows how power — embodied here by the High King's censorship — can rewrite history, turning a tragedy into a silence that endures for millennia.
